## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 59(a)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/59) provides the AMT Foreign Tax Credit, a per-category limitation that parallels [§ 904(d)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section904&num=0&edition=prelim) but uses the AMTI base instead of regular taxable income. [§ 55(a)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/55) then takes the final AMT as `max(0, tentative_min_tax − AMTFTC − regular_tax_after_FTC)` — when regular FTC fully offsets US tax on foreign-source income but AMTFTC is independently limited, the residual AMT binds. The F-US-1 reviewer flagged exactly this pattern as the silent gap: prior to this stage, US25-21 omitted the AMT addend and total_tax silently understated the AMT-binding posture.

